story.title: Fatal Consequences - Episode 2
story.storyDescription: Jo-Jo awakens, trapped in the wreckage of her car, covered in blood. The last 48 hours of her life are a blank, and the dead man beside her . . . is a total stranger.

messages.text: 48 hours earlier.
Where are you?
Almost there. Don‚Äôt worry‚Äî
Once I‚Äôve got the recording, I‚Äôll tie up the loose ends.
You‚Äôre certain you can take care of this girl?
Let‚Äôs just say the senator‚Äôs favorite dominatrix won‚Äôt be flogging any more bottoms.
Pity. It put him in such a good mood.
Guess a happy senator is a submissive senator?
And vice-versa.
Cute.
Of course, once he sees the instant replay he‚Äôll never be happy again.
There won‚Äôt be any trace of her?
None. I‚Äôll sanitize everything. It‚Äôll be like she never existed.
Perfect.
A few miles away, at Arlo‚Äôs Goodnight Diner, Jo-Jo has been laying low and working as a waitress.
Jo-Jo, Lizzy‚Äôs running late again. Can you handle one more before you split?
Sure thing, Boss.
She turns to the tattooed man who just walked in.
Have a seat anywhere, mister.
Thanks.
Can I get you a cup of coffee?
That‚Äôd be great.
I recommend tonight‚Äôs special. Arlo‚Äôs meatloaf is a party in your mouth.
Hmm. Comes with mashed potatoes. Can I have fries instead?
Of course.
You know in France, French fries are called pommes frites? ‚ÄúFried apples.‚Äù
Jo-Jo instantly recognizes the signal.
She glances up as the bell over the door chimes as Lizzy walks in.
Then she looks back down, studying the tattooed man in front of her.
Forrester?
One and the same.
Nice to finally put a face to the name.
We‚Äôve done quite a few of these gigs together, haven‚Äôt we?
That we have. You got the recording?
Not here.
Close by?
Close enough. You have the funds?
I could have wired them to your offshore account.
Wires have a way of getting crossed.
Not taking any chances, huh?
Not if I can help it. Make an excuse to leave. I‚Äôll meet you in the parking lot.
Forrester spits his coffee back into his cup.
Is this from FUCKING YESTERDAY?!
I‚Äôm sorry, sir, let me get you another cup.
Is there a problem here?
Yeah, this dumb-ass bitch just served me lukewarm turd water.
Sir, I think you need to leave.
I‚Äôm not going anywhere. Haven‚Äôt you ever heard that the customer is always right?!
Hell with that! This is my place and I reserve the right to refuse anyone who pisses me off.
Consider yourself refused, pal. Out!
Forrester dumps his coffee on the floor, splattering the liquid onto Jo-Jo‚Äôs shoes.
Guess your shift just got a little longer with that cleanup duty.
I asked you to leave. If you‚Äôre not out the door in 10 seconds I‚Äôll mop the floor with your head.
Forrester exits. Arlo makes a step to follow, but Jo-Jo pulls him back.
Leave him alone, Arlo. It‚Äôs not worth it.
Yeah, I guess.
As Jo-Jo wipes up the mess, a chill runs through her.
Something definitely feels off. Forrester‚Äôs reaction felt over the top.
Why did he have to spill coffee on her?
Hey Boss, I‚Äôm gonna head out.
You want me to walk you to your car?
Nah, that jerk-off‚Äôs halfway to Wyoming by now. See you tomorrow.
Ma√±ana.
In the kitchen, Jo-Jo makes a split-second decision.
She unhooks her pendant ‚Äî a gold cross camouflaging the USB with the recording‚Äî
And she buries it in the freezer. Then she grabs her leftovers, and heads out to the parking lot.
Is that it?
This? No, it‚Äôs meatloaf.
You‚Äôre shitting me.
Nope. Really is a party in your mouth.
Let‚Äôs get going.
Everything okay?
Why?
That scene was a little intense.
You didn‚Äôt have to dump your coffee on my shoes.
Sorry. I was trying to sell it.
Forget it. You have the payment or what?
It‚Äôs in my bag.
Show me.
Not here. In the car. Which one‚Äôs yours?
That old Volvo.
Get in.
The money?
Forrester opens his bag, pulls out a gun, and points it at Jo-Jo.
I‚Äôve got a better idea. You give me the recording or I blow your brains out.
You‚Äôll never find it if you do.
Maybe not, but I think you‚Äôll give it to me. I can be very persuasive.
It‚Äôs not on me. But I can take you to where it‚Äôs hidden‚Ä¶
Then what are you waiting for? Drive!
Jo-Jo reaches toward the seat.
Hey, what‚Äôre you doing?
Buckling up. It‚Äôs the law.
Forrester smirks. He buckles up as well.
What? You can do it and I can‚Äôt?
15 minutes later, Jo-Jo feels exhausted. Her mind‚Äôs been working overtime as she drives up a winding mountain road.
Not knowing where else to go, she leads them toward the cut-off for Grange Ravine.
How much further?
Half a mile.
You could just tell me where it is.
So you can shoot me sooner rather than later?
Quick and painless or slow and agonizing ‚Äî your call.
It‚Äôs in an abandoned deer stand. I doubt you‚Äôd find it, much less be able to haul your fat ass up there.
I should just off you right now.
You know, I thought you might pull something like this.
I made a copy for insurance. If anything happens to me‚Ä¶
Aw, c‚Äômon, Jo. Nice try, but that‚Äôs not your M.O.
Maybe I‚Äôve changed.
Doubtful. Granted, your rules are your own, but if I learned anything from working with you, it‚Äôs that you‚Äôre strictly by the book.
You were testing me?
Unfortunately, you passed. You signed your own death warrant, kiddo.
Killing me was part of the deal?
No loose ends. Ironically, our head honcho still thinks I‚Äôm delivering the goods as promised.
What?
Much as the Client wants your little BDSM scene, I‚Äôm guessing the senator will want it more ‚Äî and he‚Äôll be willing to pay for it.
A bidding war?
And may the one with the deepest pockets win.
You‚Äôre double-crossing both of us?
Sad but true.
We there yet or what? There doesn‚Äôt seem to be much more to this road.
Nope. This is the end.
And if I‚Äôm gonna die, I‚Äôm taking you with me.
Jo-Jo steps on the gas and grabs for the gun.
In the struggle, she manages to unclip Forrester‚Äôs seat belt as the car plows through the guardrail.
See you in hell, Forrester!
